# Plugin `tool_classes` Declaration

When editing a plugin manifest, every tool listed under
`provides.tools` must have a matching entry in `tool_classes`. The
host classifier falls back to brittle prefix heuristics otherwise —
several known false-positives are documented in
[`_skip_items_rca_v11.md`](mdc:_skip_items_rca_v11.md) §2.3.

## How to choose a class

1. Run the audit script to get a suggestion:
   ```powershell
   .venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\audit_tool_classes.py --plugin <id> --format table
   ```
2. Take **high-confidence** suggestions as-is.
3. Hand-review **medium / low / unknown** rows. The script's
   `--format patch` mode prints the evidence chain.
4. Never ship `unknown` as a deliberate declaration — it is the
   safety-by-default sentinel.

See the full guide:
[`docs/plugin-tool-classes-howto.md`](mdc:docs/plugin-tool-classes-howto.md)

## ApprovalClass values (lower-case strings)

`readonly_global` · `readonly_scoped` · `readonly_search` ·
`mutating_scoped` · `mutating_global` · `destructive` ·
`exec_low_risk` · `exec_capable` · `control_plane` · `interactive` ·
`network_out` · `unknown`

## Manifest shape

```jsonc
{
  "provides": { "tools": ["my_tool", "my_other_tool"] },
  "tool_classes": {
    "my_tool": "network_out",
    "my_other_tool": "readonly_scoped"
  }
}
```

## Roadmap context

This is part of the §A.1 incremental backfill from
[`docs/follow-ups/skipped-items-roadmap.md`](mdc:docs/follow-ups/skipped-items-roadmap.md).
When coverage reaches >=95 % across `plugins/**` and
`plugins-archive/**`, the manifest schema will escalate `tool_classes`
from optional to required (§A.2). Until then:

* **DO** declare classes for every new tool you add.
* **DO** run the audit before opening a PR that touches a plugin manifest.
* **DO NOT** mark `tool_classes` `required` in
  `src/openakita/plugins/manifest.py` yet — the §A.2 deferred
  validator stub in `installer.py` is the right hook point.
* **DO NOT** auto-apply low / medium / unknown suggestions blindly.

See also `.cursor/rules/add-internal-tool.mdc` for the in-tree
counterpart (declaring `TOOL_CLASSES` on built-in handlers).
